article.headline: Princeton 75, Columbia 52
article.story: PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Judson Wallace scored 17 of his game-high 24 points in the second half as Princeton rolled to a 75-52 victory over Columbia Friday night. It was the Tigers' fifth straight win to improve to 16-7 overall and 9-1 in the Ivy League. They have a 1 1/2-game lead over Brown and a two-game lead over Penn with four to play. Columbia fell to 8-16 and 4-7 in the league. The decisive 13-0 run gave the Tigers a 58-39 lead. Wallace sank a three-pointer to start the run, then Scott Greenman delivered a pretty bounce pass to Will Venable for a layup. Venable got another layup and a free throw, and, after an offensive rebound by Harrison Schaen, Wallace hit a three from the left wing to make it 56-39. Wallace, who has scored 20 or more points in each of the last five games, scored the first nine of the second half, then Scott Greenman converted a steal into a layup for a 45-35 advantage. Princeton got off to a torrid start, shooting a season-high 72 percent from the field in the first half. Greenman scored the opening basket on a drive and then hit two consecutive three-pointers to push the lead to 10-2. The Tigers' freshmen, Max Schafer and Luke Owings, then got into the act and the Tigers built a 13-point lead at 27-14. But the Lions went on an 11-2 run to cut it to 29-25. Then Owings made a steal resulting in two free throws by Venable and hit a three from the corner as the shot clock was winding down, making it 34-25.
